19// Evaluate a float polynomial efficiently, taking instruction latency
20// into account. The high order terms come first. n is the number of
21// terms, which is the degree plus one.
22namespace {
23
24Expr evaluate_polynomial(Expr x, float *coeff, int n) {
25 internal_assert(n >= 2);
26
27 Expr x2 = x * x;
28
29 Expr even_terms = coeff[0];
30 Expr odd_terms = coeff[1];
31
32 for (int i = 2; i < n; i++) {
33 if ((i & 1) == 0) {
34 if (coeff[i] == 0.0f) {
35 even_terms *= x2;
36 } else {
37 even_terms = even_terms * x2 + coeff[i];
38 }
39 } else {
40 if (coeff[i] == 0.0f) {
41 odd_terms *= x2;
42 } else {
43 odd_terms = odd_terms * x2 + coeff[i];
44 }
45 }
46 }
47
48 if ((n & 1) == 0) {
49 return even_terms * std::move(x) + odd_terms;
50 } else {
51 return odd_terms * std::move(x) + even_terms;
52 }
53}

55Expr stringify(const std::vector<Expr> &args) {
56 if (args.empty()) {
57 return Expr("");
58 }
59
60 return Internal::Call::make(type_of<const char *>(), Internal::Call::stringify,
61 args, Internal::Call::Intrinsic);
62}
63
64Expr combine_strings(const std::vector<Expr> &args) {
65 // Insert spaces between each expr.
66 std::vector<Expr> strings(args.size() * 2);
67 for (size_t i = 0; i < args.size(); i++) {
68 strings[i * 2] = args[i];
69 if (i < args.size() - 1) {
70 strings[i * 2 + 1] = Expr(" ");
71 } else {
72 strings[i * 2 + 1] = Expr("\n");
73 }
74 }
75
76 return stringify(strings);
77}

83bool is_const(const Expr &e) {
84 if (e.as<IntImm>() ||
85 e.as<UIntImm>() ||
86 e.as<FloatImm>() ||
87 e.as<StringImm>()) {
88 return true;
89 } else if (const Cast *c = e.as<Cast>()) {
90 return is_const(c->value);
91 } else if (const Ramp *r = e.as<Ramp>()) {
92 return is_const(r->base) && is_const(r->stride);
93 } else if (const Broadcast *b = e.as<Broadcast>()) {
94 return is_const(b->value);
95 } else {
96 return false;
97 }
98}
99
100bool is_const(const Expr &e, int64_t value) {
101 if (const IntImm *i = e.as<IntImm>()) {
102 return i->value == value;
103 } else if (const UIntImm *i = e.as<UIntImm>()) {
104 return (value >= 0) && (i->value == (uint64_t)value);
105 } else if (const FloatImm *i = e.as<FloatImm>()) {
106 return i->value == value;
107 } else if (const Cast *c = e.as<Cast>()) {
108 return is_const(c->value, value);
109 } else if (const Broadcast *b = e.as<Broadcast>()) {
110 return is_const(b->value, value);
111 } else {
112 return false;
113 }
114}
115
116bool is_no_op(const Stmt &s) {
117 if (!s.defined()) {
118 return true;
119 }
120 const Evaluate *e = s.as<Evaluate>();
121 return e && is_pure(e->value);
122}

126class ExprIsPure : public IRGraphVisitor {
127 using IRVisitor::visit;
128
129 void visit(const Call *op) override {
130 if (!op->is_pure()) {
131 result = false;
132 } else {
133 IRGraphVisitor::visit(op);
134 }
135 }
136
137 void visit(const Load *op) override {
138 if (!op->image.defined() && !op->param.defined()) {
139 // It's a load from an internal buffer, which could
140 // mutate.
141 result = false;
142 } else {
143 IRGraphVisitor::visit(op);
144 }
145 }
146
147public:
148 bool result = true;
149};

153bool is_pure(const Expr &e) {

155 e.accept(&pure);

195bool is_const_power_of_two_integer(const Expr &e, int *bits) {
196 if (!(e.type().is_int() || e.type().is_uint())) {
197 return false;
198 }
199
200 const Broadcast *b = e.as<Broadcast>();
201 if (b) {
202 return is_const_power_of_two_integer(b->value, bits);
203 }
204
205 const Cast *c = e.as<Cast>();
206 if (c) {
207 return is_const_power_of_two_integer(c->value, bits);
208 }
209
210 uint64_t val = 0;
211
212 if (const int64_t *i = as_const_int(e)) {
213 if (*i < 0) {
214 return false;
215 }
216 val = (uint64_t)(*i);
217 } else if (const uint64_t *u = as_const_uint(e)) {
218 val = *u;
219 }
220
221 if (val && ((val & (val - 1)) == 0)) {
222 *bits = 0;
223 for (; val; val >>= 1) {
224 if (val == 1) {
225 return true;
226 }
227 (*bits)++;
228 }
229 }
230
231 return false;
232}

234bool is_positive_const(const Expr &e) {
235 if (const IntImm *i = e.as<IntImm>()) {
236 return i->value > 0;
237 }
238 if (const UIntImm *u = e.as<UIntImm>()) {
239 return u->value > 0;
240 }
241 if (const FloatImm *f = e.as<FloatImm>()) {
242 return f->value > 0.0f;
243 }
244 if (const Cast *c = e.as<Cast>()) {
245 Type to = c->type;
246 Type from = c->value.type();
247 if (!to.is_int_or_uint() || to.can_represent(from)) {
248 // Either the cast does not lose information, or it's a
249 // non-integral cast, so no overflow behavior to worry about.
250 return is_positive_const(c->value);
251 }
252 }
253 if (const Ramp *r = e.as<Ramp>()) {
254 // slightly conservative
255 return is_positive_const(r->base) && is_positive_const(r->stride);
256 }
257 if (const Broadcast *b = e.as<Broadcast>()) {
258 return is_positive_const(b->value);
259 }
260 return false;
261}
262
263bool is_negative_const(const Expr &e) {
264 if (const IntImm *i = e.as<IntImm>()) {
265 return i->value < 0;
266 }
267 if (const FloatImm *f = e.as<FloatImm>()) {
268 return f->value < 0.0f;
269 }
270 if (const Cast *c = e.as<Cast>()) {
271 Type to = c->type;
272 Type from = c->value.type();
273 if (to.is_uint()) {
274 // Early out.
275 return false;
276 }
277 if (!to.is_int_or_uint() || to.can_represent(from)) {
278 // Either the cast does not lose information, or it's a
279 // non-integral cast, so no overflow behavior to worry about.
280 return is_negative_const(c->value);
281 }
282 }
283 if (const Ramp *r = e.as<Ramp>()) {
284 // slightly conservative
285 return is_negative_const(r->base) && is_negative_const(r->stride);
286 }
287 if (const Broadcast *b = e.as<Broadcast>()) {
288 return is_negative_const(b->value);
289 }
290 return false;
291}

300bool is_const_zero(const Expr &e) {
301 if (const IntImm *int_imm = e.as<IntImm>()) {
302 return int_imm->value == 0;
303 }
304 if (const UIntImm *uint_imm = e.as<UIntImm>()) {
305 return uint_imm->value == 0;
306 }
307 if (const FloatImm *float_imm = e.as<FloatImm>()) {
308 return float_imm->value == 0.0;
309 }
310 if (const Cast *c = e.as<Cast>()) {
311 return is_const_zero(c->value);
312 }
313 if (const Broadcast *b = e.as<Broadcast>()) {
314 return is_const_zero(b->value);
315 }
316 if (const Call *c = e.as<Call>()) {
317 return (c->is_intrinsic(Call::bool_to_mask) || c->is_intrinsic(Call::cast_mask)) &&
318 is_const_zero(c->args[0]);
319 }
320 return false;
321}
322
323bool is_const_one(const Expr &e) {
324 if (const IntImm *int_imm = e.as<IntImm>()) {
325 return int_imm->value == 1;
326 }
327 if (const UIntImm *uint_imm = e.as<UIntImm>()) {
328 return uint_imm->value == 1;
329 }
330 if (const FloatImm *float_imm = e.as<FloatImm>()) {
331 return float_imm->value == 1.0;
332 }
333 if (const Cast *c = e.as<Cast>()) {
334 return is_const_one(c->value);
335 }
336 if (const Broadcast *b = e.as<Broadcast>()) {
337 return is_const_one(b->value);
338 }
339 if (const Call *c = e.as<Call>()) {
340 return (c->is_intrinsic(Call::bool_to_mask) || c->is_intrinsic(Call::cast_mask)) &&
341 is_const_one(c->args[0]);
342 }
343 return false;
344}

348template<typename T>
349Expr make_const_helper(Type t, T val) {
350 if (t.is_vector()) {
351 return Broadcast::make(make_const(t.element_of(), val), t.lanes());
352 } else if (t.is_int()) {
353 return IntImm::make(t, (int64_t)val);
354 } else if (t.is_uint()) {
355 return UIntImm::make(t, (uint64_t)val);
356 } else if (t.is_float()) {
357 return FloatImm::make(t, (double)val);
358 } else {
359 internal_error << "Can't make a constant of type " << t << "\n";
360 return Expr();
361 }
362}

411Expr lossless_cast(Type t, Expr e) {
412 if (!e.defined() || t == e.type()) {
413 return e;
414 } else if (t.can_represent(e.type())) {
415 return cast(t, std::move(e));
416 }
417
418 if (const Cast *c = e.as<Cast>()) {
419 if (c->type.can_represent(c->value.type())) {
420 // We can recurse into widening casts.
421 return lossless_cast(t, c->value);
422 } else {
423 return Expr();
424 }
425 }
426
427 if (const Broadcast *b = e.as<Broadcast>()) {
428 Expr v = lossless_cast(t.element_of(), b->value);
429 if (v.defined()) {
430 return Broadcast::make(v, b->lanes);
431 } else {
432 return Expr();
433 }
434 }
435
436 if (const IntImm *i = e.as<IntImm>()) {
437 if (t.can_represent(i->value)) {
438 return make_const(t, i->value);
439 } else {
440 return Expr();
441 }
442 }
443
444 if (const UIntImm *i = e.as<UIntImm>()) {
445 if (t.can_represent(i->value)) {
446 return make_const(t, i->value);
447 } else {
448 return Expr();
449 }
450 }
451
452 if (const FloatImm *f = e.as<FloatImm>()) {
453 if (t.can_represent(f->value)) {
454 return make_const(t, f->value);
455 } else {
456 return Expr();
457 }
458 }
459
460 if ((t.is_int() || t.is_uint()) && t.bits() >= 16) {
461 if (const Add *add = e.as<Add>()) {
462 // If we can losslessly narrow the args even more
463 // aggressively, we're good.
464 // E.g. lossless_cast(uint16, (uint32)(some_u8) + 37)
465 // = (uint16)(some_u8) + 37
466 Expr a = lossless_cast(t.narrow(), add->a);
467 Expr b = lossless_cast(t.narrow(), add->b);
468 if (a.defined() && b.defined()) {
469 return cast(t, a) + cast(t, b);
470 } else {
471 return Expr();
472 }
473 }
474
475 if (const Sub *sub = e.as<Sub>()) {
476 Expr a = lossless_cast(t.narrow(), sub->a);
477 Expr b = lossless_cast(t.narrow(), sub->b);
478 if (a.defined() && b.defined()) {
479 return cast(t, a) + cast(t, b);
480 } else {
481 return Expr();
482 }
483 }
484
485 if (const Mul *mul = e.as<Mul>()) {
486 Expr a = lossless_cast(t.narrow(), mul->a);
487 Expr b = lossless_cast(t.narrow(), mul->b);
488 if (a.defined() && b.defined()) {
489 return cast(t, a) * cast(t, b);
490 } else {
491 return Expr();
492 }
493 }
494
495 if (const VectorReduce *reduce = e.as<VectorReduce>()) {
496 const int factor = reduce->value.type().lanes() / reduce->type.lanes();
497 switch (reduce->op) {
498 case VectorReduce::Add:
499 // A horizontal add requires one extra bit per factor
500 // of two in the reduction factor. E.g. a reduction of
501 // 8 vector lanes down to 2 requires 2 extra bits in
502 // the output. We only deal with power-of-two types
503 // though, so just make sure the reduction factor
504 // isn't so large that it will more than double the
505 // number of bits required.
506 if (factor < (1 << (t.bits() / 2))) {
507 Type narrower = reduce->value.type().with_bits(t.bits() / 2);
508 Expr val = lossless_cast(narrower, reduce->value);
509 if (val.defined()) {
510 val = cast(narrower.with_bits(t.bits()), val);
511 return VectorReduce::make(reduce->op, val, reduce->type.lanes());
512 }
513 }
514 break;
515 case VectorReduce::Max:
516 case VectorReduce::Min: {
517 Expr val = lossless_cast(t, reduce->value);
518 if (val.defined()) {
519 return VectorReduce::make(reduce->op, val, reduce->type.lanes());
520 }
521 break;
522 }
523 default:
524 break;
525 }
526 }
527 }
528
529 if (const Shuffle *shuf = e.as<Shuffle>()) {
530 std::vector<Expr> vecs;
531 for (const auto &vec : shuf->vectors) {
532 vecs.emplace_back(lossless_cast(t.with_lanes(vec.type().lanes()), vec));
533 if (!vecs.back().defined()) {
534 return Expr();
535 }
536 }
537 return Shuffle::make(vecs, shuf->indices);
538 }
539
540 return Expr();
541}
542
543Expr lossless_negate(const Expr &x) {
544 if (const Mul *m = x.as<Mul>()) {
545 Expr b = lossless_negate(m->b);
546 if (b.defined()) {
547 return Mul::make(m->a, b);
548 }
549 Expr a = lossless_negate(m->a);
550 if (a.defined()) {
551 return Mul::make(a, m->b);
552 }
553 } else if (const Call *m = Call::as_intrinsic(x, {Call::widening_mul})) {
554 Expr b = lossless_negate(m->args[1]);
555 if (b.defined()) {
556 return widening_mul(m->args[0], b);
557 }
558 Expr a = lossless_negate(m->args[0]);
559 if (a.defined()) {
560 return widening_mul(a, m->args[1]);
561 }
562 } else if (const IntImm *i = x.as<IntImm>()) {
563 if (!i->type.is_min(i->value)) {
564 return IntImm::make(i->type, -i->value);
565 }
566 } else if (const FloatImm *f = x.as<FloatImm>()) {
567 return FloatImm::make(f->type, -f->value);
568 } else if (const Cast *c = x.as<Cast>()) {
569 Expr value = lossless_negate(c->value);
570 if (value.defined()) {
571 // This works for constants, but not other things that
572 // could possibly be negated.
573 value = lossless_cast(c->type, value);
574 if (value.defined()) {
575 return value;
576 }
577 }
578 } else if (const Ramp *r = x.as<Ramp>()) {
579 Expr base = lossless_negate(r->base);
580 Expr stride = lossless_negate(r->stride);
581 // slightly conservative
582 if (base.defined() && stride.defined()) {
583 return Ramp::make(base, stride, r->lanes);
584 }
585 } else if (const Broadcast *b = x.as<Broadcast>()) {
586 Expr value = lossless_negate(b->value);
587 if (value.defined()) {
588 return Broadcast::make(value, b->lanes);
589 }
590 }
591
592 return Expr();
593}

595void check_representable(Type dst, int64_t x) {
596 if (dst.is_handle()) {
597 user_assert(dst.can_represent(x))
598 << "Integer constant " << x
599 << " will be implicitly coerced to type " << dst
600 << ", but Halide does not support pointer arithmetic.\n";
601 } else {
602 user_assert(dst.can_represent(x))
603 << "Integer constant " << x
604 << " will be implicitly coerced to type " << dst
605 << ", which changes its value to " << make_const(dst, x)
606 << ".\n";
607 }
608}

610void match_lanes(Expr &a, Expr &b) {
611 // Broadcast scalar to match vector
612 if (a.type().is_scalar() && b.type().is_vector()) {
613 a = Broadcast::make(std::move(a), b.type().lanes());
614 } else if (a.type().is_vector() && b.type().is_scalar()) {
615 b = Broadcast::make(std::move(b), a.type().lanes());
616 } else {
617 internal_assert(a.type().lanes() == b.type().lanes()) << "Can't match types of differing widths";
618 }
619}
620
621void match_types(Expr &a, Expr &b) {
622 if (a.type() == b.type()) {
623 return;
624 }
625
626 user_assert(!a.type().is_handle() && !b.type().is_handle())
627 << "Can't do arithmetic on opaque pointer types: "
628 << a << ", " << b << "\n";
629
630 match_lanes(a, b);
631
632 Type ta = a.type(), tb = b.type();
633
634 // If type broadcasting has made the types match no additional casts are needed
635 if (ta == tb) {
636 return;
637 }
638
639 if (!ta.is_float() && tb.is_float()) {
640 // int(a) * float(b) -> float(b)
641 // uint(a) * float(b) -> float(b)
642 a = cast(tb, std::move(a));
643 } else if (ta.is_float() && !tb.is_float()) {
644 b = cast(ta, std::move(b));
645 } else if (ta.is_float() && tb.is_float()) {
646 // float(a) * float(b) -> float(max(a, b))
647 if (ta.bits() > tb.bits()) {
648 b = cast(ta, std::move(b));
649 } else {
650 a = cast(tb, std::move(a));
651 }
652 } else if (ta.is_uint() && tb.is_uint()) {
653 // uint(a) * uint(b) -> uint(max(a, b))
654 if (ta.bits() > tb.bits()) {
655 b = cast(ta, std::move(b));
656 } else {
657 a = cast(tb, std::move(a));
658 }
659 } else if (!ta.is_float() && !tb.is_float()) {
660 // int(a) * (u)int(b) -> int(max(a, b))
661 int bits = std::max(ta.bits(), tb.bits());
662 int lanes = a.type().lanes();
663 a = cast(Int(bits, lanes), std::move(a));
664 b = cast(Int(bits, lanes), std::move(b));
665 } else {
666 internal_error << "Could not match types: " << ta << ", " << tb << "\n";
667 }
668}
669
670// Cast to the wider type of the two. Already guaranteed to leave
671// signed/unsigned on number of lanes unchanged.
672void match_bits(Expr &x, Expr &y) {
673 // The signedness doesn't match, so just match the bits.
674 if (x.type().bits() < y.type().bits()) {
675 x = cast(x.type().with_bits(y.type().bits()), x);
676 } else if (y.type().bits() < x.type().bits()) {
677 y = cast(y.type().with_bits(x.type().bits()), y);
678 }
679}
680
681void match_types_bitwise(Expr &x, Expr &y, const char *op_name) {
682 user_assert(x.defined() && y.defined()) << op_name << " of undefined Expr\n";
683 user_assert(x.type().is_int() || x.type().is_uint())
684 << "The first argument to " << op_name << " must be an integer or unsigned integer";
685 user_assert(y.type().is_int() || y.type().is_uint())
686 << "The second argument to " << op_name << " must be an integer or unsigned integer";
687 user_assert(y.type().is_int() == x.type().is_int())
688 << "Arguments to " << op_name
689 << " must be both be signed or both be unsigned.\n"
690 << "LHS type: " << x.type() << " RHS type: " << y.type() << "\n"
691 << "LHS value: " << x << " RHS value: " << y << "\n";
692
693 // Broadcast scalar to match vector
694 if (x.type().is_scalar() && y.type().is_vector()) {
695 x = Broadcast::make(std::move(x), y.type().lanes());
696 } else if (x.type().is_vector() && y.type().is_scalar()) {
697 y = Broadcast::make(std::move(y), x.type().lanes());
698 } else {
699 internal_assert(x.type().lanes() == y.type().lanes()) << "Can't match types of differing widths";
700 }
701
702 // Cast to the wider type of the two.
703 match_bits(x, y);
704}

706// Fast math ops based on those from Syrah (http://github.com/boulos/syrah). Thanks, Solomon!

708// Factor a float into 2^exponent * reduced, where reduced is between 0.75 and 1.5
709void range_reduce_log(const Expr &input, Expr *reduced, Expr *exponent) {
710 Type type = input.type();
711 Type int_type = Int(32, type.lanes());
712 Expr int_version = reinterpret(int_type, input);
713
714 // single precision = SEEE EEEE EMMM MMMM MMMM MMMM MMMM MMMM
715 // exponent mask = 0111 1111 1000 0000 0000 0000 0000 0000
716 // 0x7 0xF 0x8 0x0 0x0 0x0 0x0 0x0
717 // non-exponent = 1000 0000 0111 1111 1111 1111 1111 1111
718 // = 0x8 0x0 0x7 0xF 0xF 0xF 0xF 0xF
719 Expr non_exponent_mask = make_const(int_type, 0x807fffff);
720
721 // Extract a version with no exponent (between 1.0 and 2.0)
722 Expr no_exponent = int_version & non_exponent_mask;
723
724 // If > 1.5, we want to divide by two, to normalize back into the
725 // range (0.75, 1.5). We can detect this by sniffing the high bit
726 // of the mantissa.
727 Expr new_exponent = no_exponent >> 22;
728
729 Expr new_biased_exponent = 127 - new_exponent;
730 Expr old_biased_exponent = int_version >> 23;
731 *exponent = old_biased_exponent - new_biased_exponent;
732
733 Expr blended = (int_version & non_exponent_mask) | (new_biased_exponent << 23);
734
735 *reduced = reinterpret(type, blended);
736}
737
738Expr halide_log(const Expr &x_full) {
739 Type type = x_full.type();
740 internal_assert(type.element_of() == Float(32));
741
742 Expr nan = Call::make(type, "nan_f32", {}, Call::PureExtern);
743 Expr neg_inf = Call::make(type, "neg_inf_f32", {}, Call::PureExtern);
744
745 Expr use_nan = x_full < 0.0f; // log of a negative returns nan
746 Expr use_neg_inf = x_full == 0.0f; // log of zero is -inf
747 Expr exceptional = use_nan | use_neg_inf;
748
749 // Avoid producing nans or infs by generating ln(1.0f) instead and
750 // then fixing it later.
751 Expr patched = select(exceptional, make_one(type), x_full);
752 Expr reduced, exponent;
753 range_reduce_log(patched, &reduced, &exponent);
754
755 // Very close to the Taylor series for log about 1, but tuned to
756 // have minimum relative error in the reduced domain (0.75 - 1.5).
757
758 float coeff[] = {
759 0.05111976432738144643f,
760 -0.11793923497136414580f,
761 0.14971993724699017569f,
762 -0.16862004708254804686f,
763 0.19980668101718729313f,
764 -0.24991211576292837737f,
765 0.33333435275479328386f,
766 -0.50000106292873236491f,
767 1.0f,
768 0.0f};
769 Expr x1 = reduced - 1.0f;
770 Expr result = evaluate_polynomial(x1, coeff, sizeof(coeff) / sizeof(coeff[0]));
771
772 result += cast(type, exponent) * logf(2.0);
773
774 result = select(exceptional, select(use_nan, nan, neg_inf), result);
775
776 // This introduces lots of common subexpressions
777 result = common_subexpression_elimination(result);
778
779 return result;
780}
781
782Expr halide_exp(const Expr &x_full) {
783 Type type = x_full.type();
784 internal_assert(type.element_of() == Float(32));
785
786 float ln2_part1 = 0.6931457519f;
787 float ln2_part2 = 1.4286067653e-6f;
788 float one_over_ln2 = 1.0f / logf(2.0f);
789
790 Expr scaled = x_full * one_over_ln2;
791 Expr k_real = floor(scaled);
792 Expr k = cast(Int(32, type.lanes()), k_real);
793
794 Expr x = x_full - k_real * ln2_part1;
795 x -= k_real * ln2_part2;
796
797 float coeff[] = {
798 0.00031965933071842413f,
799 0.00119156835564003744f,
800 0.00848988645943932717f,
801 0.04160188091348320655f,
802 0.16667983794100929562f,
803 0.49999899033463041098f,
804 1.0f,
805 1.0f};
806 Expr result = evaluate_polynomial(x, coeff, sizeof(coeff) / sizeof(coeff[0]));
807
808 // Compute 2^k.
809 int fpbias = 127;
810 Expr biased = k + fpbias;
811
812 Expr inf = Call::make(type, "inf_f32", {}, Call::PureExtern);
813
814 // Shift the bits up into the exponent field and reinterpret this
815 // thing as float.
816 Expr two_to_the_n = reinterpret(type, biased << 23);
817 result *= two_to_the_n;
818
819 // Catch overflow and underflow
820 result = select(biased < 255, result, inf);
821 result = select(biased > 0, result, make_zero(type));
822
823 // This introduces lots of common subexpressions
824 result = common_subexpression_elimination(result);
825
826 return result;
827}
828
829Expr halide_erf(const Expr &x_full) {
830 user_assert(x_full.type() == Float(32)) << "halide_erf only works for Float(32)";
831
832 // Extract the sign and magnitude.
833 Expr sign = select(x_full < 0, -1.0f, 1.0f);
834 Expr x = abs(x_full);
835
836 // An approximation very similar to one from Abramowitz and
837 // Stegun, but tuned for values > 1. Takes the form 1 - P(x)^-16.
838 float c1[] = {0.0000818502f,
839 -0.0000026500f,
840 0.0009353904f,
841 0.0081960206f,
842 0.0430054424f,
843 0.0703310579f,
844 1.0f};
845 Expr approx1 = evaluate_polynomial(x, c1, sizeof(c1) / sizeof(c1[0]));
846
847 approx1 = 1.0f - pow(approx1, -16);
848
849 // An odd polynomial tuned for values < 1. Similar to the Taylor
850 // expansion of erf.
851 float c2[] = {-0.0005553339f,
852 0.0048937243f,
853 -0.0266849239f,
854 0.1127890132f,
855 -0.3761207240f,
856 1.1283789803f};
857
858 Expr approx2 = evaluate_polynomial(x * x, c2, sizeof(c2) / sizeof(c2[0]));
859 approx2 *= x;
860
861 // Switch between the two approximations based on the magnitude.
862 Expr y = select(x > 1.0f, approx1, approx2);
863
864 Expr result = common_subexpression_elimination(sign * y);
865
866 return result;
867}
868
869Expr raise_to_integer_power(Expr e, int64_t p) {
870 Expr result;
871 if (p == 0) {
872 result = make_one(e.type());
873 } else if (p == 1) {
874 result = std::move(e);
875 } else if (p < 0) {
876 result = make_one(e.type());
877 result /= raise_to_integer_power(std::move(e), -p);
878 } else {
879 // p is at least 2
880 if (p & 1) {
881 Expr y = raise_to_integer_power(e, p >> 1);
882 result = y * y * std::move(e);
883 } else {
884 e = raise_to_integer_power(std::move(e), p >> 1);
885 result = e * e;
886 }
887 }
888 return result;
889}

891void split_into_ands(const Expr &cond, std::vector<Expr> &result) {
892 if (!cond.defined()) {
893 return;
894 }
895 internal_assert(cond.type().is_bool()) << "Should be a boolean condition\n";
896 if (const And *a = cond.as<And>()) {
897 split_into_ands(a->a, result);
898 split_into_ands(a->b, result);
899 } else if (!is_const_one(cond)) {
900 result.push_back(cond);
901 }
902}

904Expr BufferBuilder::build() const {
905 std::vector<Expr> args(10);
906 if (buffer_memory.defined()) {
907 args[0] = buffer_memory;
908 } else {
909 Expr sz = Call::make(Int(32), Call::size_of_halide_buffer_t, {}, Call::Intrinsic);
910 args[0] = Call::make(type_of<struct halide_buffer_t *>(), Call::alloca, {sz}, Call::Intrinsic);
911 }
912
913 std::string shape_var_name = unique_name('t');
914 Expr shape_var = Variable::make(type_of<halide_dimension_t *>(), shape_var_name);
915 if (shape_memory.defined()) {
916 args[1] = shape_memory;
917 } else if (dimensions == 0) {
918 args[1] = make_zero(type_of<halide_dimension_t *>());
919 } else {
920 args[1] = shape_var;
921 }
922
923 if (host.defined()) {
924 args[2] = host;
925 } else {
926 args[2] = make_zero(type_of<void *>());
927 }
928
929 if (device.defined()) {
930 args[3] = device;
931 } else {
932 args[3] = make_zero(UInt(64));
933 }
934
935 if (device_interface.defined()) {
936 args[4] = device_interface;
937 } else {
938 args[4] = make_zero(type_of<struct halide_device_interface_t *>());
939 }
940
941 args[5] = (int)type.code();
942 args[6] = type.bits();
943 args[7] = dimensions;
944
945 std::vector<Expr> shape;
946 for (size_t i = 0; i < (size_t)dimensions; i++) {
947 if (i < mins.size()) {
948 shape.push_back(mins[i]);
949 } else {
950 shape.emplace_back(0);
951 }
952 if (i < extents.size()) {
953 shape.push_back(extents[i]);
954 } else {
955 shape.emplace_back(0);
956 }
957 if (i < strides.size()) {
958 shape.push_back(strides[i]);
959 } else {
960 shape.emplace_back(0);
961 }
962 // per-dimension flags, currently unused.
963 shape.emplace_back(0);
964 }
965 for (const Expr &e : shape) {
966 internal_assert(e.type() == Int(32))
967 << "Buffer shape fields must be int32_t:" << e << "\n";
968 }
969 Expr shape_arg = Call::make(type_of<halide_dimension_t *>(), Call::make_struct, shape, Call::Intrinsic);
970 if (shape_memory.defined()) {
971 args[8] = shape_arg;
972 } else if (dimensions == 0) {
973 args[8] = make_zero(type_of<halide_dimension_t *>());
974 } else {
975 args[8] = shape_var;
976 }
977
978 Expr flags = make_zero(UInt(64));
979 if (host_dirty.defined()) {
980 flags = select(host_dirty,
981 make_const(UInt(64), halide_buffer_flag_host_dirty),
982 make_zero(UInt(64)));
983 }
984 if (device_dirty.defined()) {
985 flags = flags | select(device_dirty,
986 make_const(UInt(64), halide_buffer_flag_device_dirty),
987 make_zero(UInt(64)));
988 }
989 args[9] = flags;
990
991 Expr e = Call::make(type_of<struct halide_buffer_t *>(), Call::buffer_init, args, Call::Extern);
992
993 if (!shape_memory.defined() && dimensions != 0) {
994 e = Let::make(shape_var_name, shape_arg, e);
995 }
996
997 return e;
998}

1000Expr strided_ramp_base(const Expr &e, int stride) {
1001 const Ramp *r = e.as<Ramp>();
1002 if (r == nullptr) {
1003 return Expr();
1004 }
1005
1006 const IntImm *i = r->stride.as<IntImm>();
1007 if (i != nullptr && i->value == stride) {
1008 return r->base;
1009 }
1010
1011 return Expr();
1012}

1259Expr fast_log(const Expr &x) {
1260 user_assert(x.type() == Float(32)) << "fast_log only works for Float(32)";
1261
1262 Expr reduced, exponent;
1263 range_reduce_log(x, &reduced, &exponent);
1264
1265 Expr x1 = reduced - 1.0f;
1266
1267 float coeff[] = {
1268 0.07640318789187280912f,
1269 -0.16252961013874300811f,
1270 0.20625219040645212387f,
1271 -0.25110261010892864775f,
1272 0.33320464908377461777f,
1273 -0.49997513376789826101f,
1274 1.0f,
1275 0.0f};
1276
1277 Expr result = evaluate_polynomial(x1, coeff, sizeof(coeff) / sizeof(coeff[0]));
1278 result = result + cast<float>(exponent) * logf(2);
1279 result = common_subexpression_elimination(result);
1280 return result;
1281}

1285// A vectorizable sine and cosine implementation. Based on syrah fast vector math
1286// https://github.com/boulos/syrah/blob/master/src/include/syrah/FixedVectorMath.h#L55
1287Expr fast_sin_cos(const Expr &x_full, bool is_sin) {
1288 const float two_over_pi = 0.636619746685028076171875f;
1289 const float pi_over_two = 1.57079637050628662109375f;
1290 Expr scaled = x_full * two_over_pi;
1291 Expr k_real = floor(scaled);
1292 Expr k = cast<int>(k_real);
1293 Expr k_mod4 = k % 4;
1294 Expr sin_usecos = is_sin ? ((k_mod4 == 1) || (k_mod4 == 3)) : ((k_mod4 == 0) || (k_mod4 == 2));
1295 Expr flip_sign = is_sin ? (k_mod4 > 1) : ((k_mod4 == 1) || (k_mod4 == 2));
1296
1297 // Reduce the angle modulo pi/2.
1298 Expr x = x_full - k_real * pi_over_two;
1299
1300 const float sin_c2 = -0.16666667163372039794921875f;
1301 const float sin_c4 = 8.333347737789154052734375e-3;
1302 const float sin_c6 = -1.9842604524455964565277099609375e-4;
1303 const float sin_c8 = 2.760012648650445044040679931640625e-6;
1304 const float sin_c10 = -2.50293279435709337121807038784027099609375e-8;
1305
1306 const float cos_c2 = -0.5f;
1307 const float cos_c4 = 4.166664183139801025390625e-2;
1308 const float cos_c6 = -1.388833043165504932403564453125e-3;
1309 const float cos_c8 = 2.47562347794882953166961669921875e-5;
1310 const float cos_c10 = -2.59630184018533327616751194000244140625e-7;
1311
1312 Expr outside = select(sin_usecos, 1, x);
1313 Expr c2 = select(sin_usecos, cos_c2, sin_c2);
1314 Expr c4 = select(sin_usecos, cos_c4, sin_c4);
1315 Expr c6 = select(sin_usecos, cos_c6, sin_c6);
1316 Expr c8 = select(sin_usecos, cos_c8, sin_c8);
1317 Expr c10 = select(sin_usecos, cos_c10, sin_c10);
1318
1319 Expr x2 = x * x;
1320 Expr tri_func = outside * (x2 * (x2 * (x2 * (x2 * (x2 * c10 + c8) + c6) + c4) + c2) + 1);
1321 return select(flip_sign, -tri_func, tri_func);
1322}
1323
1324} // namespace

1326Expr fast_sin(const Expr &x_full) {
1327 return fast_sin_cos(x_full, true);
1328}

1330Expr fast_cos(const Expr &x_full) {
1331 return fast_sin_cos(x_full, false);

1333
1334Expr fast_exp(const Expr &x_full) {
1335 user_assert(x_full.type() == Float(32)) << "fast_exp only works for Float(32)";
1336
1337 Expr scaled = x_full / logf(2.0);
1338 Expr k_real = floor(scaled);
1339 Expr k = cast<int>(k_real);
1340 Expr x = x_full - k_real * logf(2.0);
1341
1342 float coeff[] = {
1343 0.01314350012789660196f,
1344 0.03668965196652099192f,
1345 0.16873890085469545053f,
1346 0.49970514590562437052f,
1347 1.0f,
1348 1.0f};
1349 Expr result = evaluate_polynomial(x, coeff, sizeof(coeff) / sizeof(coeff[0]));
1350
1351 // Compute 2^k.
1352 int fpbias = 127;
1353 Expr biased = clamp(k + fpbias, 0, 255);
1354
1355 // Shift the bits up into the exponent field and reinterpret this
1356 // thing as float.
1357 Expr two_to_the_n = reinterpret<float>(biased << 23);
1358 result *= two_to_the_n;
1359 result = common_subexpression_elimination(result);
1360 return result;
1361}

1399Expr saturating_cast(Type t, Expr e) {
1400 // For float to float, guarantee infinities are always pinned to range.
1401 if (t.is_float() && e.type().is_float()) {
1402 if (t.bits() < e.type().bits()) {
1403 e = cast(t, clamp(std::move(e), t.min(), t.max()));
1404 } else {
1405 e = clamp(cast(t, std::move(e)), t.min(), t.max());
1406 }
1407 } else if (e.type() != t) {
1408 // Limits for Int(2^n) or UInt(2^n) are not exactly representable in Float(2^n)
1409 if (e.type().is_float() && !t.is_float() && t.bits() >= e.type().bits()) {
1410 e = max(std::move(e), t.min()); // min values turn out to be always representable
1411
1412 // This line depends on t.max() rounding upward, which should always
1413 // be the case as it is one less than a representable value, thus
1414 // the one larger is always the closest.
1415 e = select(e >= cast(e.type(), t.max()), t.max(), cast(t, e));
1416 } else {
1417 Expr min_bound;
1418 if (!e.type().is_uint()) {
1419 min_bound = lossless_cast(e.type(), t.min());
1420 }
1421 Expr max_bound = lossless_cast(e.type(), t.max());
1422
1423 if (min_bound.defined() && max_bound.defined()) {
1424 e = clamp(std::move(e), min_bound, max_bound);
1425 } else if (min_bound.defined()) {
1426 e = max(std::move(e), min_bound);
1427 } else if (max_bound.defined()) {
1428 e = min(std::move(e), max_bound);
1429 }
1430 e = cast(t, std::move(e));
1431 }
1432 }
1433 return e;
1434}
1435
1436Expr select(Expr condition, Expr true_value, Expr false_value) {
1437 if (as_const_int(condition)) {
1438 // Why are you doing this? We'll preserve the select node until constant folding for you.
1439 condition = cast(Bool(), std::move(condition));
1440 }
1441
1442 // Coerce int literals to the type of the other argument
1443 if (as_const_int(true_value)) {
1444 true_value = cast(false_value.type(), std::move(true_value));
1445 }
1446 if (as_const_int(false_value)) {
1447 false_value = cast(true_value.type(), std::move(false_value));
1448 }
1449
1450 user_assert(condition.type().is_bool())
1451 << "The first argument to a select must be a boolean:\n"
1452 << " " << condition << " has type " << condition.type() << "\n";
1453
1454 user_assert(true_value.type() == false_value.type())
1455 << "The second and third arguments to a select do not have a matching type:\n"
1456 << " " << true_value << " has type " << true_value.type() << "\n"
1457 << " " << false_value << " has type " << false_value.type() << "\n";
1458
1459 return Internal::Select::make(std::move(condition), std::move(true_value), std::move(false_value));
1460}

1462Tuple tuple_select(const Tuple &condition, const Tuple &true_value, const Tuple &false_value) {
1463 user_assert(condition.size() == true_value.size() && true_value.size() == false_value.size())
1464 << "tuple_select() requires all Tuples to have identical sizes.";
1465 Tuple result(std::vector<Expr>(condition.size()));
1466 for (size_t i = 0; i < result.size(); i++) {
1467 result[i] = select(condition[i], true_value[i], false_value[i]);
1468 }
1469 return result;
1470}

1482Expr mux(const Expr &id, const std::vector<Expr> &values) {
1483 user_assert(!values.empty()) << "mux() requires a non-empty vector of values";
1484 if (values.size() == 1) {
1485 // Useful in generic code where the size of the values vector
1486 // might be degenerate.
1487 return values[0];
1488 }
1489
1490 // Check if all the values have the same type.
1491 Type t = values[0].type();
1492 for (int i = 1; i < (int)values.size(); i++) {
1493 user_assert(values[i].type() == t) << "mux() requires all the values to have the same type.";
1494 }
1495 std::vector<Expr> result{id};
1496 result.insert(result.end(), values.begin(), values.end());
1497 return Internal::Call::make(t, Internal::Call::mux, result, Internal::Call::Intrinsic);
1498}

1508Expr unsafe_promise_clamped(const Expr &value, const Expr &min, const Expr &max) {
1509 user_assert(value.defined()) << "unsafe_promise_clamped with undefined value.\n";

1511 Expr n_max_val = max.defined() ? lossless_cast(value.type(), max) : value.type().max();
1512

1516 Internal::Call::unsafe_promise_clamped,
1517 {value, n_min_val, n_max_val},
1518 Internal::Call::Intrinsic);
1519}

1872
1873Expr cast(Type t, Expr a) {
1874 user_assert(a.defined()) << "cast of undefined Expr\n";
1875 if (a.type() == t) {
1876 return a;
1877 }
1878
1879 if (t.is_handle() && !a.type().is_handle()) {
1880 user_error << "Can't cast \"" << a << "\" to a handle. "
1881 << "The only legal cast from scalar types to a handle is: "
1882 << "reinterpret(Handle(), cast<uint64_t>(" << a << "));\n";
1883 } else if (a.type().is_handle() && !t.is_handle()) {
1884 user_error << "Can't cast handle \"" << a << "\" to type " << t << ". "
1885 << "The only legal cast from handles to scalar types is: "
1886 << "reinterpret(UInt(64), " << a << ");\n";
1887 }
1888
1889 // Fold constants early
1890 if (const int64_t *i = as_const_int(a)) {
1891 return Internal::make_const(t, *i);
1892 }
1893 if (const uint64_t *u = as_const_uint(a)) {
1894 return Internal::make_const(t, *u);
1895 }
1896 if (const double *f = as_const_float(a)) {
1897 return Internal::make_const(t, *f);
1898 }
1899
1900 if (t.is_vector()) {
1901 if (a.type().is_scalar()) {
1902 return Internal::Broadcast::make(cast(t.element_of(), std::move(a)), t.lanes());
1903 } else if (const Internal::Broadcast *b = a.as<Internal::Broadcast>()) {
1904 internal_assert(b->lanes == t.lanes());
1905 return Internal::Broadcast::make(cast(t.element_of(), b->value), t.lanes());
1906 }
1907 }
1908 return Internal::Cast::make(t, std::move(a));
1909}

1911Expr clamp(Expr a, const Expr &min_val, const Expr &max_val) {
1912 user_assert(a.defined() && min_val.defined() && max_val.defined())
1913 << "clamp of undefined Expr\n";
1914 Expr n_min_val = lossless_cast(a.type(), min_val);
1915 user_assert(n_min_val.defined())
1916 << "Type mismatch in call to clamp. First argument ("
1917 << a << ") has type " << a.type() << ", but second argument ("
1918 << min_val << ") has type " << min_val.type() << ". Use an explicit cast.\n";
1919 Expr n_max_val = lossless_cast(a.type(), max_val);
1920 user_assert(n_max_val.defined())
1921 << "Type mismatch in call to clamp. First argument ("
1922 << a << ") has type " << a.type() << ", but third argument ("
1923 << max_val << ") has type " << max_val.type() << ". Use an explicit cast.\n";
1924 return Internal::Max::make(Internal::Min::make(std::move(a), std::move(n_max_val)), std::move(n_min_val));
1925}

2316Expr reinterpret(Type t, Expr e) {
2317 user_assert(e.defined()) << "reinterpret of undefined Expr\n";
2318 int from_bits = e.type().bits() * e.type().lanes();
2319 int to_bits = t.bits() * t.lanes();
2320 user_assert(from_bits == to_bits)
2321 << "Reinterpret cast from type " << e.type()
2322 << " which has " << from_bits
2323 << " bits, to type " << t
2324 << " which has " << to_bits << " bits\n";
2325 return Internal::Call::make(t, Internal::Call::reinterpret, {std::move(e)}, Internal::Call::PureIntrinsic);
2326}

2426Expr lerp(Expr zero_val, Expr one_val, Expr weight) {
2427 user_assert(zero_val.defined()) << "lerp with undefined zero value";
2428 user_assert(one_val.defined()) << "lerp with undefined one value";
2429 user_assert(weight.defined()) << "lerp with undefined weight";
2430
2431 // We allow integer constants through, so that you can say things
2432 // like lerp(0, cast<uint8_t>(x), alpha) and produce an 8-bit
2433 // result. Note that lerp(0.0f, cast<uint8_t>(x), alpha) will
2434 // produce an error, as will lerp(0.0f, cast<double>(x),
2435 // alpha). lerp(0, cast<float>(x), alpha) is also allowed and will
2436 // produce a float result.
2437 if (as_const_int(zero_val)) {
2438 zero_val = cast(one_val.type(), std::move(zero_val));
2439 }
2440 if (as_const_int(one_val)) {
2441 one_val = cast(zero_val.type(), std::move(one_val));
2442 }
2443
2444 user_assert(zero_val.type() == one_val.type())
2445 << "Can't lerp between " << zero_val << " of type " << zero_val.type()
2446 << " and " << one_val << " of different type " << one_val.type() << "\n";
2447 user_assert((weight.type().is_uint() || weight.type().is_float()))
2448 << "A lerp weight must be an unsigned integer or a float, but "
2449 << "lerp weight " << weight << " has type " << weight.type() << ".\n";
2450 user_assert((zero_val.type().is_float() || zero_val.type().bits() <= 32))
2451 << "Lerping between 64-bit integers is not supported\n";
2452 // Compilation error for constant weight that is out of range for integer use
2453 // as this seems like an easy to catch gotcha.
2454 if (!zero_val.type().is_float()) {
2455 const double *const_weight = as_const_float(weight);
2456 if (const_weight) {
2457 user_assert(*const_weight >= 0.0 && *const_weight <= 1.0)
2458 << "Floating-point weight for lerp with integer arguments is "
2459 << *const_weight << ", which is not in the range [0.0, 1.0].\n";
2460 }
2461 }
2462 Type t = zero_val.type();
2463 return Internal::Call::make(t, Internal::Call::lerp,
2464 {std::move(zero_val), std::move(one_val), std::move(weight)},
2465 Internal::Call::PureIntrinsic);
2466}

2525Expr random_float(Expr seed) {
2526 // Random floats get even IDs
2527 static std::atomic<int> counter{0};
2528 int id = (counter++) * 2;
2529
2530 std::vector<Expr> args;
2531 if (seed.defined()) {
2532 user_assert(seed.type() == Int(32))
2533 << "The seed passed to random_float must have type Int(32), but instead is "
2534 << seed << " of type " << seed.type() << "\n";
2535 args.push_back(std::move(seed));
2536 }
2537 args.emplace_back(id);
2538
2539 // This is (surprisingly) pure - it's a fixed psuedo-random
2540 // function of its inputs.
2541 return Internal::Call::make(Float(32), Internal::Call::random,
2542 args, Internal::Call::PureIntrinsic);
2543}
2544
2545Expr random_uint(Expr seed) {
2546 // Random ints get odd IDs
2547 static std::atomic<int> counter{0};
2548 int id = (counter++) * 2 + 1;
2549
2550 std::vector<Expr> args;
2551 if (seed.defined()) {
2552 user_assert(seed.type() == Int(32) || seed.type() == UInt(32))
2553 << "The seed passed to random_int must have type Int(32) or UInt(32), but instead is "
2554 << seed << " of type " << seed.type() << "\n";
2555 args.push_back(std::move(seed));
2556 }
2557 args.emplace_back(id);
2558
2559 return Internal::Call::make(UInt(32), Internal::Call::random,
2560 args, Internal::Call::PureIntrinsic);
2561}
2562
2563Expr random_int(Expr seed) {
2564 return cast<int32_t>(random_uint(std::move(seed)));
2565}
